5","1426–1485":"1426–1485","1430–1451":"1430–1451","1451–1483":"1451–1483","1400–Male":"1400–Afdød","1404–Female":"1404–Afdød","1426":"1426","August 1485":"august 1485","1404":"1404","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1430":"1430","1485":"1485","1451":"1451","1483":"1483","1604":"1604","10 January 1451":"10. januar 1451","Berkshire, England":"Berkshire, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Chedworth, Gloucestershire, England":"Chedworth, Gloucestershire, England","Walleye, Berkshire, England":"Berkshire, England","Glasgow, Sterling, Scotland":"Glasgow, Lanarkshire, Skotland","Battle of Bosworth Field, England":"Battle, Sussex, England"},"nl":{"1426–August 1485":"1426–augustus 1485","1426–1485":"1426–1485","1430–1451":"1430–1451","1451–1483":"1451–1483","1400–Male":"1400–Overleden","1404–Female":"1404–Overleden","1426":"1426","August 1485":"augustus 1485","1404":"1404","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1430":"1430","1485":"1485","1451":"1451","1483":"1483","1604":"1604","10 January 1451":"10 januari 1451","Berkshire, England":"Berkshire, England","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Chedworth, Gloucestershire, England":"Chedworth, Gloucestershire, England","Walleye, Berkshire, England":"Berkshire, England","Glasgow, Sterling, Scotland":"Glasgow, Lanarkshire, Schotland","Battle of Bosworth Field, England":"Battle, Sussex, England"},"en":{"1426–August 1485":"1426–August 1485","1426–1485":"1426–1485","1430–1451":"1430–1451","1451–1483":"1451–1483","1400–Male":"1400–Deceased","1404–Female":"1404–Deceased","1426":"1426","August 1485":"August 1485","1404":"1404","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1430":"1430","1485":"1485","1451":"1451","1483":"1483","1604":"1604","10 January 1451":"10 January 1451","Berkshire, England":"Berkshire, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Chedworth, Gloucestershire, England":"Chedworth, Gloucestershire, England","Walleye, Berkshire, England":"Berkshire, England","Glasgow, Sterling, Scotland":"Glasgow, Lanarkshire, Scotland","Battle of Bosworth Field, England":"Battle, Sussex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]},{"name":"La","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["variant of   Olaf  , also widely used in southwest Sweden."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Bere","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the various names containing this syllable as a first or second element, for example   Albert   and   Bertram .   See also  Burt ."],"variants":[{"name":"Bertram","meanings":["From an Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’ + <i>hramn</i> ‘raven’. Ravens were traditional symbols of wisdom in Germanic mythology; Odin was regularly accompanied by ravens called Hugin and Munin. This name was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain.  See also  Bertrand ."]},{"name":"Bertrand","meanings":["Medieval French variant of   Bertram  , imported to Britain by the Normans. In modern times it has been made famous by the English philosopher  Bertrand Russell  (  1872–1970 ), but is only in occasional use."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":29,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard La Bere Wynninge was born in 1426, in Berkshire, England, his fathe